<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910919-0001</DOCNO><DOCID>910919-0001.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   In-Flight Phone Seeks   To Offer Live News,   Sports on Airliners</HL><DATE>09/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   AMR DAL GCI NWA U</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>AIRLINES (AIR)MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)TELEPHONE SYSTEMS, INCLUDING CELLULAR (TLS)</IN><NS>SCIENCE andamp; TECHNOLOGY (SCN)</NS><RE>GEORGIA (GA)MINNESOTA (MN)NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)VIRGINIA (VA)ILLINOIS (IL)</RE><LP>   OAK BROOK, Ill. -- In-Flight Phone Corp. said it filedwith the Federal Communications Commision for an experimentallicense to offer airline passengers live sports, news andentertainment programs on twelve audio channels.   As a supplement to its air-to-ground communicationsservice, closely held In-Flight plans to offer passengerseverything from &quot;play-by-play sports action to the PhilDonahue show,&quot; a spokesman said.</LP><TEXT>   The company would service the carriers through all-digitaltransmission. Passengers could pay by the game to hearsporting events; other news and entertainment programs wouldbe free through sponsors, the spokesman said.   Under an earlier license, In-Flight next month will beginits air-to-ground service, which allows travelers using aportable laptop computer or facsimile machine to sendmessages to the ground through a data jack in the armrest.   Carriers that offer the air-to-ground service, such as AMRCorp.'s American, USAir Group Inc.'s airline unit and NWAInc.'s Northwest, could supplement it with the live sportsand news service early next year, In-Flight said.   Gannett Co.'s USA Today Sky Radio also plans to launch alive radio service for airline passengers sometime next year.   Delta Air Lines already signed up to offer the broadcast,which USA Today said it will transmit via satellite to audiosystems already in place in many commercial carriers.   In-Flight was founded by Jack D. Goeken, the one-time headof GTE Corp.'s Airfone unit, who left Airfone andsubsequently formed what has become its biggest rival.</TEXT></DOC>